{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 10:33:12.231993", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos EBGP fabric\nDate: now\n\nScope and goal\n- Objective: analyze current network state (control-plane and data-plane) and identify any anomalies, localize faulty devices and determine root cause(s) where present.\n- Resources used: reachability sweep from hosts, FRR BGP config & running-config & route tables on all routers, host and router interface/config dumps.\n\nExecutive summary / overall health\n- The fabric is converged and functioning. BGP sessions are established end‑to‑end and all expected /24 host subnets (10.<pod>.<leaf>.0/24) are present in BGP on super‑spine, spine and leaf routers.\n- Data‑plane tests show successful host‑to‑host reachability across pods with 0% packet loss for sampled tests (ping results from hosts such as pc_0_0, pc_0_1 to a variety of remote hosts all succeeded). No end‑to‑end blackholes were observed in the sampled tests.\n- Routing is multi‑path where expected (Clos equal‑cost/multipath behavior). Route propagation appears consistent between leaves, spines and the super‑spine.\n\nDetailed findings\n\n1) Data‑plane reachability\n- Results summary (from reachability sweep): all tested inter‑host pings succeeded (examples: pc_0_0 -> pc_1_1 0% loss, RTTs in expected low‑ms range). No packet loss or high jitter anomalies reported in the provided ping subset.\n- Hosts' local networking is correct: pc_0_0 has 10.0.0.2/24 with default via 10.0.0.1; pc_0_1 has 10.0.1.2/24 with default via 10.0.1.1.\n\n2) Control‑plane (BGP) state and route visibility\n- All routers show FRR running and BGP configured. BGP neighbor statements exist for expected /31 interconnects across the fabric. No neighbor is reported as down in the provided BGP outputs.\n- Route propagation:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) is advertising and locally connected to 10.0.0.0/24 (C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected; BGP shows network 10.0.0.0/24).\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201) is advertising and locally connected to 10.0.1.0/24.\n  - Spines (65100, 65101) and super‑spine (65000) have learned and installed the /24s and present them in their BGP tables; super‑spine shows multiple next‑hops for each prefix (expected from EBGP peering to multiple spines/leaves).\n- Routing tables on routers show connected /31 interconnect addresses (all expected 172.16.x.x/31 links are present and installed as connected routes).\n- Many prefixes are visible as multipath (multiple equal/parallel paths), consistent with a Clos/fat‑tree multi‑path design.\n\n3) Device/interface state (sampled)\n- leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 interfaces are up, all configured /31s present, and leaf interfaces to hosts (eth8) have host /24 IPs:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 eth8 = 10.0.0.1/24 (serves pc_0_0)\n  - leaf_router_0_1 eth8 = 10.0.1.1/24 (serves pc_0_1)\n- No RX/TX errors or collisions reported in the ifconfig output for the inspected interfaces.\n\nObserved anomalies / noteworthy items\n- Unusual router-id on super_spine_router_0:\n  - The super_spine router's BGP router-id is 172.16.0.0. Using an address that ends with .0 (network address) as a router-id is unusual (typically a loopback or an interface IP is used). Functionally this does not appear to have caused convergence issues here, but it is noteworthy because it is not a conventional choice and could cause confusion in debugging or if another router uses the same id.\n- Debugging enabled on production routers (informational, not a direct fault):\n  - All FRR instances show debug bgp keepalives and debug bgp updates in/out enabled in the running-config. This increases log verbosity and could be intentional for troubleshooting, but retained debug flags could generate noisy logs if left enabled long term.\n- No BGP session drops or route withdrawals seen in the captured snapshots; however the outputs are snapshots and do not show historical flaps. Nothing in the provided outputs indicates active instability.\n- Multipath/equal‑cost differences across spines:\n  - There are multiple valid paths for many prefixes (expected), and the selected best path differs across spines/leafs per BGP decision process. This is normal for load balancing in Clos, but will produce asymmetric forwarding depending on the chosen best path. Asymmetry itself is expected and not an error unless application‑level issues are observed.\n\nLocalization (devices with relevant evidence)\n- super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000)\n  - BGP table populated with the /24s, next‑hops to many spines/leaves.\n  - Router‑id unusual (172.16.0.0).\n  - Control-plane appears healthy (routes selected and FIB entries present).\n- spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 (AS 65100 / 65101)\n  - Both have full BGP tables with multipath entries to leaf prefixes; connected /31s appear healthy.\n- leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) and leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201)\n  - Both advertise their attached /24 networks (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 respectively).\n  - Their routing tables show learned routes and the local host subnets are present and reachable.\n- Hosts (pc_0_0, pc_0_1)\n  - Interface and IP configurations match expected subnets and default gateway settings.\n  - Sampled reachability is good.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Given the evidence, there is no operational failure detected — both control-plane (BGP) and data-plane (ping tests and installed routes) show normal, converged behavior. Therefore there is no root cause of a service outage to identify from the provided data.\n- The only items flagged as potentially problematic (but not currently impacting connectivity) are:\n  - super_spine_router_0 using 172.16.0.0 as its BGP router‑id (non‑standard choice). This is an anomaly in configuration style, not a cause of route loss in current snapshots.\n  - debug logging enabled across FRR instances (operational/administrative concern rather than a failure cause).\n\nConclusion\n- Network is healthy and converged according to the provided snapshots: BGP sessions are up, prefixes are being propagated, FIB entries exist, and host reachability checks passed with no loss.\n- No control‑plane or data‑plane faults were identified from the supplied outputs.\n- Minor configuration oddities (router‑id choice on the super‑spine and debug flags enabled) were observed; these are recommended to be reviewed but are not causing observable failures now.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- (only if requested) run targeted additional checks: BGP neighbor states summary, show bgp neighbors detail for specific peers, continuous ping or traceroute to inspect path asymmetry for a particular host pair, or examine FRR logs to check for historical flaps.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 66694, "output_tokens": 3038, "total_tokens": 69732, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 8960}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1408}}}
